'''Kusanagi Shrine''' (くさなぎじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Yamakiri, {{ill|lt=Shimizu-ku|Q79385|qid=Q79385|1=Shimizu-ku, Shizuoka}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka|Q174691|qid=Q174691|1=Shizuoka (city)}}, {{ill|lt=Shizuoka Prefecture|Q131320|qid=Q131320|1=Shizuoka Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} and its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|qid=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

=== Summary ===
The founding era is unknown. Shrine tradition says that when {{ill|lt=Yamato Takeru|Q461258|qid=Q461258|lt=Yamato Takeru-no-Mikoto|1=Yamato Takeru}} made his eastern campaign, he established a main sanctuary here, and later when {{ill|lt=Kibi Takehiko|Q18226257|qid=Q18226257|1=Kibi no Takehiko}}, vice commander of that campaign, came to rule this area, he built shrine buildings at the former main sanctuary and enshrined Yamato Takeru. It was once also called "Kyūman-hassen-sha" (Ninety-eight-thousand Shrine), said to have enshrined 98,000 people who accompanied Yamato Takeru's eastern campaign, and at rites 98,000 {{ill|lt=heihaku offerings|Q11481885|qid=Q11481885|1=Hanpei}} were dedicated.

The oldest record in documents appears in the '{{ill|lt=Suruga no Kuni Fudoki|Q11668491|qid=Q11668491|1=Suruga no Kuni Fudoki}}', saying official offerings were presented in year 1 of {{ill|lt=Emperor Seimu|Q316672|qid=Q316672|1=Emperor Seimu}} (133). In a variant text of the Ruijū Rikkokushi, it says that in year 1 of {{ill|lt=Jōgan (Japan)|Q1075635|qid=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} (859) it was granted Junior Second Rank in the {{ill|lt=shinkai|Q11591025|qid=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} divine rank system.

In the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}' it is listed as "Kusanagi Shrine, Ihara District, Suruga Province," ranked as small shrine. Since {{ill|lt=Kusanagi Shrine|Q11618229|qid=Q11618229|1=Kusanagi Shrine}} in Udo District (present Shimizu-ku Kusanagi), also a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, has the same name and also enshrines Yamato Takeru, this shrine was called "East Kusanagi Shrine" until the Edo period to distinguish them. In Meiji 6 it became a {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}, returning to the original name Kusanagi Shrine.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Yamato Takeru|Q461258|qid=Q461258|lt=Yamato Takeru-no-Mikoto|1=Yamato Takeru}} (main deity)
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ototachibana-hime-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}
* {{ill|lt=Kibi Takehiko|Q18226257|qid=Q18226257|lt=Kibi Takehiko-no-Mikoto|1=Kibi no Takehiko}}
* Ōtomo no Takehi no Muraji no Mikoto
* Kashiwade no Nanatsukumu-sune no Mikoto
* {{ill|lt=Wakatakehiko-no-Mikoto|Q11596350|qid=Q11596350|1=Wakatakehiko}}
* Misuki-tomo-mimi-takehiko no Mikoto

